Thank you to our Silver Tier Sponsor Waveform Plastics!

Waveform Plastics helps the team with canopy thermoforming, molding polycarbonate sheets into the shape of the canopy. Earlier this year, Waveform Plastics helped the team test a new technique called drape forming to improve the optical clarity.

In a typical thermoforming process, a plastic sheet is heated until pliable, afterwards a vacuum is pulled underneath to shape the part onto a mold. However, this technique often leaves even the smallest deformations and imperfections on the mold surface.

With drape forming, we apply no vacuum underneath - instead, the hot polycarbonate sheet is directly dropped on to the mold and formed by hand. With this technique we achieved exceptional optical clarity and we hope to apply a similar technique with our next-generation vehicle.

Thank you Steve, Neil, and everyone at Waveform Plastics for giving us this opportunity and supporting the team!

Learn more about them at waveformplastics.com

This past summer, the team completely overhauled our low-voltage system with the primary goal to develop a central control board for all logic functionality of the car. On October 17th, the LEAP program, in collaboration with Engineers Without Borders @ewbuoft , hosted the workshop: ‚ÄúSpace Debris and Tomorrow‚Äôs Missions: The Impact on Our Future in Space.‚Äù üå†

Participants explored the critical issue of space debris‚Äîhow it‚Äôs affecting us today and what it means for the future of space exploration ‚Äî through engaging discussions and activities.

#UTAT #RedefiningLimits #SpaceExploration #Sustainability #Innovation

Redefining Limits in Aerospace: The University of Toronto Aerospace Team (UTAT) is the University of Toronto‚Äôs aerospace design team. The team is split into four divisions, Rocketry, UAS, Space Systems, and Aerospace Policy, each looking to make a positive mark in the aerospace field. Rocketry, which builds solid, hybrid, and liquid rockets, sets records at launch competitions. UAS, which works on drones and fixed-wing planes, has made a name for itself in its competitions, building for challenges based on environmental and transport problems facing the real world. Space Systems, which builds satellites, became recognized internationally with the launch of the student-built HERON Mk. II into space with Space X. Aerospace Policy, which conducts research and attends international conferences to present their ideas, advocates for the creation of equitable and well-defined policies for the continuing progress of aerospace. Each division makes it a core value to progress the aerospace field with cutting-edge technology, while fostering its leaders and innovators of tomorrow.

Redefining Limits in the Community: The University of Toronto Aerospace Team‚Äôs (UTAT) outreach team consistently seeks opportunities to engage the community, sharing its love of aerospace and all its facets with members from all walks of life. Outreach events UTAT has attended in the past include the Science Rendezvous where team members shot bottle rockets with young and old Torontonians. High-school programs are also another way for UTAT to connect with the community, this gives us the opportunity to engage with high schoolers to get them excited for university life. Elementary programs are also another opportunity for us to introduce the wonderful world of aerospace to elementary students. UTAT believes aerospace should be accessible to everybody, regardless of age or experience, and that there is no better way to encourage Canadians then by going out and meeting them!

It provides a way for undergraduate students outside of the aerospace major to get practical, hands-on knowledge of the technical field they love so much. This summer, members competed in the Banaue Lodge Competition held by Terraviva. They were tasked to reimagine a sustainable lodging structure that promotes local traditions and tourism of Banaue Rice Terraces while harnessing the essence of this UNESCO site. 

Team members: Ambareen Fatima, Chidubem Nwokeocha, Emma Saville and Sara Oureshi.

‚ÄúDue to the decline in the Banaue‚Äôs population and the commodification of their culture, Ifugo traditions have become disturbed with the ideals of tourism. Payoh Bale Lodge aims to reverse this trend by incorporating traditional Ifugao elements into its design as a method of cultural preservation and education for tourists. Inspired by the architecture in Batad Philippines, this proposal serves as a lodge in the Banaue area. Using local and traditional materials, the design respects and appreciates the Ifugao Houses, a traditional structure in the Philippines.‚Äù
